Id>0000-0003-0625-3829</gtr:orcidId><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=G106%2F1242"><gtr:id>5B92115A-9FAB-4A1C-855E-39F1E6D20B71</gtr:id><gtr:title>Readmission for exacerbation of COPD: psycho-social risk factors and symptom perception amongst community-based elderl</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>G106/1242</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) is a progressive lung disease often known as emphysema and chronic bronchitis, and most commonly caused by smoking. In the UK nearly 1.5 million may be affected. Acute attacks of breathlessness are a common symptom of COPD and can be serious, leading to hospitalisation and premature death. People with COPD are also often socially isolated, and experience feelings of stress, anxiety and depression, especially outside the normal working hours of most support services. We know much about the way lung function affects patients? health and quality of life, but little about the ways in which social and psycholgical factors might be associated with poor health outcomes in people with COPD. By recruiting and following a large sample of COPD patients this study aims to better understand whether patients? social and psychological health are linked with higher risks for hospital admission. It is hoped that the results of the study will be used in planning and implementing a range of social and psychological interventions to support and improve the lives of COPD patients who suffer from low levels of social support and anxious and depressive symptoms.</gtr:abstractText><gtr:technicalSummary>Background: chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) is a leading cause of ill health, disability and death in adults. In England and Wales, 28 000 people died from COPD in 1999, almost equal the number of lung cancer deaths. Among the most severely affected, acute exacerbations are a common cause of hospital admission. Hospitalisation for acute exacerbation of COPD is associated with a high risk of readmission and premature death. Social isolation, depression, fatigue and high rates of physical disability are common too, especially among the elderly, and may contribute to relapse and readmission.

Aims: there is much research into clinical risk factors for readmission but less is known about whether patients? social environment may also contribute to risk of readmission. Additionally, the extent to which elderly patients comprehend and cope with their disease is not well understood. This research aims to investigate and describe how elderly patients? social environment and perception of their illness may impact on their healthcare-seeking behaviour.

Methods: a prospective longitudinal cohort study of the relationship between non-clinical and clinical factors and readmission in patients discharged from Wythenshawe Hospital and the Manchester Royal Infirmary for COPD exacerbation. Information about socio-demographic, environmental, lifestyle and clinical factors potentially related to admission will be collected at baseline. Disability and usual physical activity will be assessed using the Manchester Respiratory Activities of Daily Living Questionnaire. Health status will be measured using the St George?s Respiratory Questionnaire. Anxiety and depression will be screened for using the Hospital Anxiety and Depression Scale. Clinical data routinely available on admission will be collected from patient case notes and from ward nurses. Each patient will be followed up for 12 months, either at outpatient chest clinics or at patients? homes. A purposive sapatients will be asked to consent to a semi-structured interview. These interviews will draw on the framework piloted by Caress et al and focus on social factors, symptom perception and coping strategies that might motivate and modulate the healthcare-seeking behaviour of patients. 

Medical and scientific opportunities: this proposed study will assemble and follow-up a unique cohort of elderly COPD patients recruited from two large urban teaching hospitals. It will further cement links between the MRI, the North West Lung Centre and the School of Nursing at the new merged University of Manchester, enabling future development and piloting of social interventions to improve the lives of community-based elderly people with COPD.</gtr:technicalSummary><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2009-08-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C"><gtr:id>C008C651-F5B0-4859-A334-5F574AB6B57C</gtr:id><gtr:name>MRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2005-09-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>180739</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>20902</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>United Kingdom</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>en_GB</gtr:currLang><gtr:department>NIHR CLAHRC for Greater Manchester</gtr:department><gtr:description>Research and Capability Funding round 6</gtr:description><gtr:end>2012-04-02</gtr:end><gtr:fundingOrg>National Institute for Health Research</gtr:fundingOrg><gtr:id>9EF153F8-2447-43BC-9DDF-3F2DA7D6FB68</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>VHbHfjEj9zM</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Public</gtr:sector><gtr:start>2011-04-01</gtr:start></gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:furtherFundingOutput><gtr:amountPounds>897342</gtr:amountPounds><gtr:country>United Kingdom of Great Britain &amp; Northern Ireland (UK)</gtr:country><gtr:currCode>GBP</gtr:currCode><gtr:currCountryCode>United Kingdom</gtr:currCountryCode><gtr:currLang>en_GB</gtr:currLang><gtr:department>School for Primary Care Resear